1)What is Virtula DOM?
The Virtual DOM is a lightweight, in-memory representation of the Real DOM.
What it is: A tree of plain JavaScript objects that describes what the UI should look like.
Why it's used: Directly updating the Real DOM (the actual browser UI) is slow and computationally expensive. Manipulating the Virtual DOM is much faster because nothing is being painted on the screen yet.
=====================================================
2) What is Re-render?
A re-render is the process where React calls your component function to generate a new Virtual DOM tree.
What triggers it: A change in a component's state or props.What happens: React runs the component code to figure out the new intended state of the UI.
It just produces a new Virtual DOM snapshot.

v.v.v.vimp React's rendering process consists of two phases:
Render Phase – React creates the new Virtual DOM and performs reconciliation.
Commit Phase – React updates the real DOM and runs lifecycle effects.
========================================================
3)What is Reconciliation?
Reconciliation (often referred to as the "diffing" algorithm) is the process of comparing the new Virtual DOM tree with the previous Virtual DOM tree.
What it does: React uses this algorithm to identify exactly what has changed (what nodes were added, removed, or updated).
The result: It creates a minimal list of changes needed to update the Real DOM. The actual process of applying these changes to the browser is called the "commit phase".
========================================================
4)What causes a component to re-render?
- State changes
-Props change
-Parent component re-renders: Even if props haven't changed, the child re-renders unless optimized with React.memo.
- A consumed context value changes.
- A subscribed global state changes.
- Its key changes or a force update occurs.
